#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:11
msgid "Adapting basic Python types"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:13
msgid ""
"Many standard Python types are adapted into SQL and returned as Python "
"objects when a query is executed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:16
msgid ""
"Converting the following data types between Python and PostgreSQL works out-"
"of-the-box and doesn't require any configuration. In case you need to "
"customise the conversion you should take a look at :ref:`adaptation`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:27
msgid "Booleans adaptation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:29
msgid ""
"Python `bool` values `!True` and `!False` are converted to the equivalent "
"`PostgreSQL boolean type`__::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:32
msgid ""
">>> cur.execute(\"SELECT %s, %s\", (True, False))\n"
"# equivalent to \"SELECT true, false\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:37
msgid "`numpy.bool_` values can be dumped too."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:50
msgid "Numbers adaptation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:54
msgid ""
"`PostgreSQL numeric types <https://www.postgresql.org/docs/current/static/"
"datatype-numeric.html>`__"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:57
msgid ""
"Python `int` values can be converted to PostgreSQL :sql:`smallint`, :sql:"
"`integer`, :sql:`bigint`, or :sql:`numeric`, according to their numeric "
"value. Psycopg will choose the smallest data type available, because "
"PostgreSQL can automatically cast a type up (e.g. passing a `smallint` where "
"PostgreSQL expect an `integer` is gladly accepted) but will not cast down "
"automatically (e.g. if a function has an :sql:`integer` argument, passing it "
"a :sql:`bigint` value will fail, even if the value is 1)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:65
msgid "Python `float` values are converted to PostgreSQL :sql:`float8`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:67
msgid ""
"Python `~decimal.Decimal` values are converted to PostgreSQL :sql:`numeric`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:69
msgid ""
"On the way back, smaller types (:sql:`int2`, :sql:`int4`, :sql:`float4`) are "
"promoted to the larger Python counterpart."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:74
msgid ""
"Sometimes you may prefer to receive :sql:`numeric` data as `!float` instead, "
"for performance reason or ease of manipulation: you can configure an adapter "
"to :ref:`cast PostgreSQL numeric to Python float <adapt-example-float>`. "
"This of course may imply a loss of precision."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:81
msgid "NumPy integer__ and `floating point`__ values can be dumped too."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:95
msgid "Strings adaptation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:99
msgid ""
"`PostgreSQL character types <https://www.postgresql.org/docs/current/"
"datatype-character.html>`__"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:102
msgid ""
"Python `str` are converted to PostgreSQL string syntax, and PostgreSQL types "
"such as :sql:`text` and :sql:`varchar` are converted back to Python `!str`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:105
msgid ""
"conn = psycopg.connect()\n"
"conn.execute(\n"
"    \"INSERT INTO menu (id, entry) VALUES (%s, %s)\",\n"
"    (1, \"Crème Brûlée at 4.99€\"))\n"
"conn.execute(\"SELECT entry FROM menu WHERE id = 1\").fetchone()[0]\n"
"'Crème Brûlée at 4.99€'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:114
msgid ""
"PostgreSQL databases `have an encoding`__, and `the session has an "
"encoding`__ too, exposed in the `!Connection.info.`\\ `~ConnectionInfo."
"encoding` attribute. If your database and connection are in UTF-8 encoding "
"you will likely have no problem, otherwise you will have to make sure that "
"your application only deals with the non-ASCII chars that the database can "
"handle; failing to do so may result in encoding/decoding errors:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:124
msgid ""
"# The encoding is set at connection time according to the db configuration\n"
"conn.info.encoding\n"
"'utf-8'\n"
"\n"
"# The Latin-9 encoding can manage some European accented letters\n"
"# and the Euro symbol\n"
"conn.execute(\"SET client_encoding TO LATIN9\")\n"
"conn.execute(\"SELECT entry FROM menu WHERE id = 1\").fetchone()[0]\n"
"'Crème Brûlée at 4.99€'\n"
"\n"
"# The Latin-1 encoding doesn't have a representation for the Euro symbol\n"
"conn.execute(\"SET client_encoding TO LATIN1\")\n"
"conn.execute(\"SELECT entry FROM menu WHERE id = 1\").fetchone()[0]\n"
"# Traceback (most recent call last)\n"
"# ...\n"
"# UntranslatableCharacter: character with byte sequence 0xe2 0x82 0xac\n"
"# in encoding \"UTF8\" has no equivalent in encoding \"LATIN1\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:144
msgid ""
"In rare cases you may have strings with unexpected encodings in the "
"database. Using the ``SQL_ASCII`` client encoding  will disable decoding of "
"the data coming from the database, which will be returned as `bytes`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:148
msgid ""
"conn.execute(\"SET client_encoding TO SQL_ASCII\")\n"
"conn.execute(\"SELECT entry FROM menu WHERE id = 1\").fetchone()[0]\n"
"b'Cr\\xc3\\xa8me Br\\xc3\\xbbl\\xc3\\xa9e at 4.99\\xe2\\x82\\xac'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:154
msgid ""
"Alternatively you can cast the unknown encoding data to :sql:`bytea` to "
"retrieve it as bytes, leaving other strings unaltered: see :ref:`adapt-"
"binary`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:157
msgid ""
"Note that PostgreSQL text cannot contain the ``0x00`` byte. If you need to "
"store Python strings that may contain binary zeros you should use a :sql:"
"`bytea` field."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:172
msgid "Binary adaptation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:174
msgid ""
"Python types representing binary objects (`bytes`, `bytearray`, "
"`memoryview`) are converted by default to :sql:`bytea` fields. By default "
"data received is returned as `!bytes`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:178
msgid ""
"If you are storing large binary data in bytea fields (such as binary "
"documents or images) you should probably use the binary format to pass and "
"return values, otherwise binary data will undergo `ASCII escaping`__, taking "
"some CPU time and more bandwidth. See :ref:`binary-data` for details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:189
msgid "Date/time types adaptation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:193
msgid ""
"`PostgreSQL date/time types <https://www.postgresql.org/docs/current/"
"datatype-datetime.html>`__"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:196
msgid ""
"Python `~datetime.date` objects are converted to PostgreSQL :sql:`date`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:197
msgid ""
"Python `~datetime.datetime` objects are converted to PostgreSQL :sql:"
"`timestamp` (if they don't have a `!tzinfo` set) or :sql:`timestamptz` (if "
"they do)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:200
msgid ""
"Python `~datetime.time` objects are converted to PostgreSQL :sql:`time` (if "
"they don't have a `!tzinfo` set) or :sql:`timetz` (if they do)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:202
msgid ""
"Python `~datetime.timedelta` objects are converted to PostgreSQL :sql:"
"`interval`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:205
msgid ""
"PostgreSQL :sql:`timestamptz` values are returned with a timezone set to the "
"`connection TimeZone setting`__, which is available as a Python `~zoneinfo."
"ZoneInfo` object in the `!Connection.info`.\\ `~ConnectionInfo.timezone` "
"attribute::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:210
msgid ""
">>> conn.info.timezone\n"
"zoneinfo.ZoneInfo(key='Europe/London')\n"
"\n"
">>> conn.execute(\"select '2048-07-08 12:00'::timestamptz\").fetchone()[0]\n"
"datetime.datetime(2048, 7, 8, 12, 0, tzinfo=zoneinfo.ZoneInfo(key='Europe/"
"London'))"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:220
msgid ""
"PostgreSQL :sql:`timestamptz` doesn't store \"a timestamp with a timezone "
"attached\": it stores a timestamp always in UTC, which is converted, on "
"output, to the connection TimeZone setting::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:224
msgid ""
">>> conn.execute(\"SET TIMEZONE to 'Europe/Rome'\")  # UTC+2 in summer\n"
"\n"
">>> conn.execute(\"SELECT '2042-07-01 12:00Z'::timestamptz\").fetchone()[0]  "
"# UTC input\n"
"datetime.datetime(2042, 7, 1, 14, 0, tzinfo=zoneinfo.ZoneInfo(key='Europe/"
"Rome'))"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:229
msgid ""
"Check out the `PostgreSQL documentation about timezones`__ for all the "
"details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:237
msgid ""
"Times with timezone are silly objects, because you cannot know the offset of "
"a timezone with daylight saving time rules without knowing the date too."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:241
msgid ""
"Although silly, times with timezone are supported both by Python and by "
"PostgreSQL. However they are only supported with fixed offset timezones: "
"Postgres :sql:`timetz` values loaded from the database will result in Python "
"`!time` objects with `!tzinfo` attributes specified as fixed offset, for "
"instance by a `~datetime.timezone` value::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:247
msgid ""
">>> conn.execute(\"SET TIMEZONE to 'Europe/Rome'\")\n"
"\n"
"# UTC+1 in winter\n"
">>> conn.execute(\"SELECT '2042-01-01 12:00Z'::timestamptz::timetz\")."
"fetchone()[0]\n"
"datetime.time(13, 0, tzinfo=datetime.timezone(datetime."
"timedelta(seconds=3600)))\n"
"\n"
"# UTC+2 in summer\n"
">>> conn.execute(\"SELECT '2042-07-01 12:00Z'::timestamptz::timetz\")."
"fetchone()[0]\n"
"datetime.time(14, 0, tzinfo=datetime.timezone(datetime."
"timedelta(seconds=7200)))"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:257
msgid ""
"Dumping Python `!time` objects is only supported with fixed offset `!"
"tzinfo`, such as the ones returned by Postgres, or by whatever `~datetime."
"tzinfo` implementation resulting in the time's `~datetime.time.utcoffset` "
"returning a value."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:266
msgid "Dates and times limits in Python"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:268
msgid ""
"PostgreSQL date and time objects can represent values that cannot be "
"represented by the Python `datetime` objects:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:271
msgid ""
"dates and timestamps after the year 9999, the special value \"infinity\";"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:272
msgid ""
"dates and timestamps before the year 1, the special value \"-infinity\";"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:273
msgid "the time 24:00:00."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:275
msgid "Loading these values will raise a `~psycopg.DataError`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:277
msgid ""
"If you need to handle these values you can define your own mapping (for "
"instance mapping every value greater than `datetime.date.max` to `!date."
"max`, or the time 24:00 to 00:00) and write a subclass of the default "
"loaders implementing the added capability; please see :ref:`this example "
"<adapt-example-inf-date>` for a reference."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:291
msgid "DateStyle and IntervalStyle limits"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:293
msgid ""
"Loading :sql:`timestamp with time zone` in text format is only supported if "
"the connection DateStyle__ is set to `ISO` format; time and time zone "
"representation in other formats is ambiguous."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:299
msgid ""
"Furthermore, at the time of writing, the only supported value for "
"IntervalStyle__ is ``postgres``; loading :sql:`interval` data in text format "
"with a different setting is not supported."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:305
msgid ""
"If your server is configured with different settings by default, you can "
"obtain a connection in a supported style using the ``options`` connection "
"parameter; for example::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:309
msgid ""
">>> conn = psycopg.connect(options=\"-c datestyle=ISO,YMD\")\n"
">>> conn.execute(\"show datestyle\").fetchone()[0]\n"
"# 'ISO, YMD'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:313
msgid ""
"These GUC parameters only affects loading in text format; loading timestamps "
"or intervals in :ref:`binary format <binary-data>` is not affected by "
"DateStyle or IntervalStyle."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:321
msgid "JSON adaptation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:323
msgid ""
"Psycopg can map between Python objects and PostgreSQL `json/jsonb types`__, "
"allowing to customise the load and dump function used."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:328
msgid ""
"Because several Python objects could be considered JSON (dicts, lists, "
"scalars, even date/time if using a dumps function customised to use them), "
"Psycopg requires you to wrap the object to dump as JSON into a wrapper: "
"either `psycopg.types.json.Json` or `~psycopg.types.json.Jsonb`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:333
msgid ""
"from psycopg.types.json import Jsonb\n"
"\n"
"thing = {\"foo\": [\"bar\", 42]}\n"
"conn.execute(\"INSERT INTO mytable VALUES (%s)\", [Jsonb(thing)])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:340
msgid ""
"By default Psycopg uses the standard library `json.dumps` and `json.loads` "
"functions to serialize and de-serialize Python objects to JSON. If you want "
"to customise how serialization happens, for instance changing serialization "
"parameters or using a different JSON library, you can specify your own "
"functions using the `psycopg.types.json.set_json_dumps()` and `~psycopg."
"types.json.set_json_loads()` functions, to apply either globally or to a "
"specific context (connection or cursor)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:348
msgid ""
"from functools import partial\n"
"from psycopg.types.json import Jsonb, set_json_dumps, set_json_loads\n"
"import ujson\n"
"\n"
"# Use a faster dump function\n"
"set_json_dumps(ujson.dumps)\n"
"\n"
"# Return floating point values as Decimal, just in one connection\n"
"set_json_loads(partial(json.loads, parse_float=Decimal), conn)\n"
"\n"
"conn.execute(\"SELECT %s\", [Jsonb({\"value\": 123.45})]).fetchone()[0]\n"
"# {'value': Decimal('123.45')}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:363
msgid ""
"If you need an even more specific dump customisation only for certain "
"objects (including different configurations in the same query) you can "
"specify a `!dumps` parameter in the `~psycopg.types.json.Json`/`~psycopg."
"types.json.Jsonb` wrapper, which will take precedence over what is specified "
"by `!set_json_dumps()`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:369
msgid ""
"from uuid import UUID, uuid4\n"
"\n"
"class UUIDEncoder(json.JSONEncoder):\n"
"    \"\"\"A JSON encoder which can dump UUID.\"\"\"\n"
"    def default(self, obj):\n"
"        if isinstance(obj, UUID):\n"
"            return str(obj)\n"
"        return json.JSONEncoder.default(self, obj)\n"
"\n"
"uuid_dumps = partial(json.dumps, cls=UUIDEncoder)\n"
"obj = {\"uuid\": uuid4()}\n"
"cnn.execute(\"INSERT INTO objs VALUES %s\", [Json(obj, dumps=uuid_dumps)])\n"
"# will insert: {'uuid': '0a40799d-3980-4c65-8315-2956b18ab0e1'}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:389
msgid "Lists adaptation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:391
msgid ""
"Python `list` objects are adapted to `PostgreSQL arrays`__ and back. Only "
"lists containing objects of the same type can be dumped to PostgreSQL (but "
"the list may contain `!None` elements)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:399
msgid ""
"If you have a list of values which you want to use with the :sql:`IN` "
"operator... don't. It won't work (neither with a list nor with a tuple)::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:402
msgid ""
">>> conn.execute(\"SELECT * FROM mytable WHERE id IN %s\", [[10,20,30]])\n"
"Traceback (most recent call last):\n"
"  File \"<stdin>\", line 1, in <module>\n"
"psycopg.errors.SyntaxError: syntax error at or near \"$1\"\n"
"LINE 1: SELECT * FROM mytable WHERE id IN $1\n"
"                                          ^"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:409
msgid ""
"What you want to do instead is to use the `'= ANY()' expression`__ and pass "
"the values as a list (not a tuple)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:414
msgid ""
"This has also the advantage of working with an empty list, whereas ``IN ()`` "
"is not valid SQL."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:424
msgid "UUID adaptation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:426
msgid ""
"Python `uuid.UUID` objects are adapted to PostgreSQL `UUID type`__ and back::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:428
msgid ""
">>> conn.execute(\"select gen_random_uuid()\").fetchone()[0]\n"
"UUID('97f0dd62-3bd2-459e-89b8-a5e36ea3c16c')\n"
"\n"
">>> from uuid import uuid4\n"
">>> conn.execute(\"select gen_random_uuid() = %s\", [uuid4()]).fetchone()"
"[0]\n"
"False  # long shot"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:441
msgid "Network data types adaptation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:443
msgid ""
"Objects from the `ipaddress` module are converted to PostgreSQL `network "
"address types`__:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:446
msgid ""
"`~ipaddress.IPv4Address`, `~ipaddress.IPv4Interface` objects are converted "
"to the PostgreSQL :sql:`inet` type. On the way back, :sql:`inet` values "
"indicating a single address are converted to `!IPv4Address`, otherwise they "
"are converted to `!IPv4Interface`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:451
msgid ""
"`~ipaddress.IPv4Network` objects are converted to the :sql:`cidr` type and "
"back."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:454
msgid ""
"`~ipaddress.IPv6Address`, `~ipaddress.IPv6Interface`, `~ipaddress."
"IPv6Network` objects follow the same rules, with IPv6 :sql:`inet` and :sql:"
"`cidr` values."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:460
msgid ""
">>> conn.execute(\"select '192.168.0.1'::inet, '192.168.0.1/24'::inet\")."
"fetchone()\n"
"(IPv4Address('192.168.0.1'), IPv4Interface('192.168.0.1/24'))\n"
"\n"
">>> conn.execute(\"select '::ffff:1.2.3.0/120'::cidr\").fetchone()[0]\n"
"IPv6Network('::ffff:102:300/120')"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:472
msgid "Enum adaptation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:476
msgid ""
"Psycopg can adapt Python `~enum.Enum` subclasses into PostgreSQL enum types "
"(created with the |CREATE TYPE AS ENUM|_ command)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:482
msgid ""
"In order to set up a bidirectional enum mapping, you should get information "
"about the PostgreSQL enum using the `~types.enum.EnumInfo` class and "
"register it using `~types.enum.register_enum()`. The behaviour of "
"unregistered and registered enums is different."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:487
msgid "If the enum is not registered with `register_enum()`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:489
msgid ""
"Pure `!Enum` classes are dumped as normal strings, using their member names "
"as value. The unknown oid is used, so PostgreSQL should be able to use this "
"string in most contexts (such as an enum or a text field)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:493
msgid ""
"In previous version dumping pure enums is not supported and raise a \"cannot "
"adapt\" error."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:497
msgid ""
"Mix-in enums are dumped according to their mix-in type (because a `class "
"MyIntEnum(int, Enum)` is more specifically an `!int` than an `!Enum`, so "
"it's dumped by default according to `!int` rules)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:501
msgid ""
"PostgreSQL enums are loaded as Python strings. If you want to load arrays of "
"such enums you will have to find their OIDs using `types.TypeInfo.fetch()` "
"and register them using `~types.TypeInfo.register()`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:505
msgid ""
"If the enum is registered (using `~types.enum.EnumInfo`\\ `!.fetch()` and "
"`~types.enum.register_enum()`):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:508
msgid "Enums classes, both pure and mixed-in, are dumped by name."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:510
msgid ""
"The registered PostgreSQL enum is loaded back as the registered Python enum "
"members."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/types/enum.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.types.enum.EnumInfo:1
msgid "Manage information about an enum type."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:515
msgid ""
"`!EnumInfo` is a subclass of `~psycopg.types.TypeInfo`: refer to the "
"latter's documentation for generic usage, especially the `~psycopg.types."
"TypeInfo.fetch()` method."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:521
msgid ""
"After `~psycopg.types.TypeInfo.fetch()`, it contains the labels defined in "
"the PostgreSQL enum type."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:526
msgid ""
"After `register_enum()` is called, it will contain the Python type mapping "
"to the registered enum."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/types/enum.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.types.enum.register_enum:1
msgid "Register the adapters to load and dump a enum type."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:0
msgid "Parameters"
msgstr "參數"

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/types/enum.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.types.enum.register_enum:3
msgid "The object with the information about the enum to register."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/types/enum.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.types.enum.register_enum:4
msgid ""
"The context where to register the adapters. If `!None`, register it globally."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/types/enum.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.types.enum.register_enum:6
msgid ""
"Python enum type matching to the PostgreSQL one. If `!None`, a new enum will "
"be generated and exposed as `EnumInfo.enum`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/types/enum.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.types.enum.register_enum:8
msgid "Override the mapping between `!enum` members and `!info` labels."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:531
msgid ""
"After registering, fetching data of the registered enum will cast PostgreSQL "
"enum labels into corresponding Python enum members."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:534
msgid ""
"If no `!enum` is specified, a new `Enum` is created based on PostgreSQL enum "
"labels."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:537
msgid "Example::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:539
msgid ""
">>> from enum import Enum, auto\n"
">>> from psycopg.types.enum import EnumInfo, register_enum\n"
"\n"
">>> class UserRole(Enum):\n"
"...     ADMIN = auto()\n"
"...     EDITOR = auto()\n"
"...     GUEST = auto()\n"
"\n"
">>> conn.execute(\"CREATE TYPE user_role AS ENUM ('ADMIN', 'EDITOR', "
"'GUEST')\")\n"
"\n"
">>> info = EnumInfo.fetch(conn, \"user_role\")\n"
">>> register_enum(info, conn, UserRole)\n"
"\n"
">>> some_editor = info.enum.EDITOR\n"
">>> some_editor\n"
"<UserRole.EDITOR: 2>\n"
"\n"
">>> conn.execute(\n"
"...     \"SELECT pg_typeof(%(editor)s), %(editor)s\",\n"
"...     {\"editor\": some_editor}\n"
"... ).fetchone()\n"
"('user_role', <UserRole.EDITOR: 2>)\n"
"\n"
">>> conn.execute(\n"
"...     \"SELECT ARRAY[%s, %s]\",\n"
"...     [UserRole.ADMIN, UserRole.GUEST]\n"
"... ).fetchone()\n"
"[<UserRole.ADMIN: 1>, <UserRole.GUEST: 3>]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:568
msgid ""
"If the Python and the PostgreSQL enum don't match 1:1 (for instance if "
"members have a different name, or if more than one Python enum should map to "
"the same PostgreSQL enum, or vice versa), you can specify the exceptions "
"using the `!mapping` parameter."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:573
msgid ""
"`!mapping` should be a dictionary with Python enum members as keys and the "
"matching PostgreSQL enum labels as values, or a list of `(member, label)` "
"pairs with the same meaning (useful when some members are repeated). Order "
"matters: if an element on either side is specified more than once, the last "
"pair in the sequence will take precedence::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:579
msgid ""
"# Legacy roles, defined in medieval times.\n"
">>> conn.execute(\n"
"...     \"CREATE TYPE abbey_role AS ENUM ('ABBOT', 'SCRIBE', 'MONK', "
"'GUEST')\")\n"
"\n"
">>> info = EnumInfo.fetch(conn, \"abbey_role\")\n"
">>> register_enum(info, conn, UserRole, mapping=[\n"
"...     (UserRole.ADMIN, \"ABBOT\"),\n"
"...     (UserRole.EDITOR, \"SCRIBE\"),\n"
"...     (UserRole.EDITOR, \"MONK\")])\n"
"\n"
">>> conn.execute(\"SELECT '{ABBOT,SCRIBE,MONK,GUEST}'::abbey_role[]\")."
"fetchone()[0]\n"
"[<UserRole.ADMIN: 1>,\n"
" <UserRole.EDITOR: 2>,\n"
" <UserRole.EDITOR: 2>,\n"
" <UserRole.GUEST: 3>]\n"
"\n"
">>> conn.execute(\"SELECT %s::text[]\", [list(UserRole)]).fetchone()[0]\n"
"['ABBOT', 'MONK', 'GUEST']"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:598
msgid ""
"A particularly useful case is when the PostgreSQL labels match the *values* "
"of a `!str`\\-based Enum. In this case it is possible to use something like "
"``{m: m.value for m in enum}`` as mapping::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/adapt.rst:602
msgid ""
">>> class LowercaseRole(str, Enum):\n"
"...     ADMIN = \"admin\"\n"
"...     EDITOR = \"editor\"\n"
"...     GUEST = \"guest\"\n"
"\n"
">>> conn.execute(\n"
"...     \"CREATE TYPE lowercase_role AS ENUM ('admin', 'editor', "
"'guest')\")\n"
"\n"
">>> info = EnumInfo.fetch(conn, \"lowercase_role\")\n"
">>> register_enum(\n"
"...     info, conn, LowercaseRole, mapping={m: m.value for m in "
"LowercaseRole})\n"
"\n"
">>> conn.execute(\"SELECT 'editor'::lowercase_role\").fetchone()[0]\n"
"<LowercaseRole.EDITOR: 'editor'>"
msgstr ""

